00:49:53.300 --> 00:49:56.050
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: You're shooting
these big fish eye pictures.

00:49:56.050 --> 00:49:59.410
Is it safe to say that
earlier in your career,

00:49:59.410 --> 00:50:01.620 position:56%
you would not have been [inaudible],

00:50:01.620 --> 00:50:07.050 position:56%
that you would have always been more
the straightforward architectural --

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:10.040
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Well, what
I'm doing a lot more photography

00:50:10.040 --> 00:50:12.840
for myself these days, and I --

00:50:12.840 --> 00:50:16.530
one of the things that I have
been doing is doing photographs

00:50:16.530 --> 00:50:18.820
that I call upshots.

00:50:18.820 --> 00:50:21.770
And for the upshots, I
take -- I will take any --

00:50:21.770 --> 00:50:25.210
I will extreme wide-angle
lenses, including fish eye lenses,

00:50:25.210 --> 00:50:29.810
because that gives you a very
different view, and yet it --

00:50:29.810 --> 00:50:33.040
I mean it's reality, but
it's a distorted reality.

00:50:33.040 --> 00:50:36.980
And it -- you can make very
interesting images I think

00:50:36.980 --> 00:50:38.320
doing that.

00:50:38.320 --> 00:50:45.060
But whether you do those as part
of an assignment, I don't know.

00:50:45.060 --> 00:50:53.070
You would have to have a client
who recognizes that, okay,

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:54.940
this is maybe not part
of the documentation

00:50:54.940 --> 00:50:56.730
but nevertheless is
an interesting take.

00:50:56.730 --> 00:50:59.520
It's because, you know,
every now and again,

00:50:59.520 --> 00:51:01.070
that sort of thing will happen.

00:51:01.070 --> 00:51:02.690
But you have to have
a flexible client.

00:51:02.690 --> 00:51:12.610
You wouldn't do it
with just any client.

00:51:12.610 --> 00:51:13.910
Yeah?

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:22.380
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: So it seems
to me that both architecture

00:51:22.380 --> 00:51:32.580
and photography have become
more classic as we get --

00:51:32.580 --> 00:51:36.770
since the advent of purists.

00:51:36.770 --> 00:51:40.760
And I'm just wondering since
you've bridged this gap

00:51:40.760 --> 00:51:46.700
in a wonderful way how the
conversation has changed

00:51:46.700 --> 00:51:48.600
between architects and
architectural photographers.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:55.360
I mean I know that it's easy to
be dictated to by the architect

00:51:55.360 --> 00:51:58.690
in a certain way, especially

00:51:58.690 --> 00:52:01.380
as their creations become
more frothy, you know?

00:52:01.380 --> 00:52:02.680
&gt;&gt; N Yeah.

00:52:02.680 --> 00:52:03.980
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: Acrobatic.

00:52:03.980 --> 00:52:05.280
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Yeah.

00:52:05.280 --> 00:52:06.580
It's an interesting
point that you bring up.

00:52:06.580 --> 00:52:09.750
As I mentioned earlier,
many, many architects are --

00:52:09.750 --> 00:52:16.770
would be or could be very talented
photographers if they had the time

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:21.340
and had the equipment to do it.

00:52:21.340 --> 00:52:25.790
However, when it comes to the
documentation of their own work,

00:52:25.790 --> 00:52:32.000 position:56%
they usually seek out a photographer
with whom they feel compatible

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:35.380 position:56%
and that they understand that once
they have worked with a photographer

00:52:35.380 --> 00:52:39.910
who has gone out and documented
something that they have done

00:52:39.910 --> 00:52:44.340
and that they like it, then
they become more trusting.

00:52:44.340 --> 00:52:45.640
And then they give -- they tend

00:52:45.640 --> 00:52:48.050
to give the photographer
less and less instruction.

00:52:48.050 --> 00:52:53.580
And that works usually to both
the benefit of the photographer

00:52:53.580 --> 00:52:57.060
and the architect because sometimes
an architect doesn't always --

00:52:57.060 --> 00:52:58.770
you know, they're so
close to the design

00:52:58.770 --> 00:53:01.800
that they don't necessarily
see it objectively.

00:53:01.800 --> 00:53:03.550 position:56%
You know, it's an interesting thing.

00:53:03.550 --> 00:53:07.730
And the other I think very
particularly interesting aspect

00:53:07.730 --> 00:53:11.070
of architectural photography
is which is more important,

00:53:11.070 --> 00:53:14.920
the quality of the
architecture or the photograph?

00:53:14.920 --> 00:53:18.940
And that's an interesting
question to pose.

00:53:18.940 --> 00:53:20.240
And it's surprising that --

00:53:20.240 --> 00:53:25.900
and quite a number of instances
you get collections of photographs

00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:28.170
of the work of a particular
architect

00:53:28.170 --> 00:53:32.850
without any acknowledgement
of who took those photographs.

00:53:32.850 --> 00:53:37.250 position:56%
And yet, they can be -- they can be
widely divergent and very different.

00:53:37.250 --> 00:53:38.870
I personally find that clients
who give me more direction end

00:53:38.870 --> 00:53:40.170
up really -- you know, sometimes,
you know, they might say, "Okay,

00:53:40.170 --> 00:53:41.470
we want it done this way."

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:42.770
Okay. You do it that way, but
you also do it your own way too,

00:53:42.770 --> 00:53:44.070
show them the two, and then
afterwards, you know what?

00:53:44.070 --> 00:53:45.370
Your way was better?

00:53:45.370 --> 00:53:46.670
[ Laughter ]

00:53:46.670 --> 00:53:47.970
Because you're -- you know,
that's really what you do.

00:53:47.970 --> 00:53:49.870
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: And in
a way you become a proxy

00:53:49.870 --> 00:53:51.170
for the first visitor.

00:53:51.170 --> 00:53:52.470
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Yeah.

00:53:52.470 --> 00:53:53.770
Yeah.

00:53:53.770 --> 00:53:59.600
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: This is the first
experience, and it's a reflection,

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:04.740
I imagine, that some architects
don't like held up to them.

00:54:04.740 --> 00:54:06.040
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Well, maybe not.

00:54:06.040 --> 00:54:07.340
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: It's a way

00:54:07.340 --> 00:54:09.560
of showing whether their
building succeeds or fails.

00:54:09.560 --> 00:54:10.860
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Yeah.

00:54:10.860 --> 00:54:12.590
Most architects recognize how
important the documentation

00:54:12.590 --> 00:54:15.730
of their buildings is because
only a certain proportion

00:54:15.730 --> 00:54:18.890
of their audience will actually get

00:54:18.890 --> 00:54:21.910
to see the finished
product in many cases.

00:54:21.910 --> 00:54:24.290
And therefore, they're
really seeing it --

00:54:24.290 --> 00:54:26.020
they're seeing an interpretation
of the design by somebody else.

00:54:26.020 --> 00:54:27.320
And that person has to
be on the same wavelength

00:54:27.320 --> 00:54:29.620
for that to be successful.

00:54:33.170 --> 00:54:36.430
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: And those
processing [inaudible] now.

00:54:36.430 --> 00:54:39.230
The building on the left
