00:55:19.380 --> 00:55:20.680
I certainly would have, yes.

00:55:20.680 --> 00:55:21.980
&gt;&gt; Male Speaker: Okay, good.

00:55:21.980 --> 00:55:23.280
That's what --

00:55:23.280 --> 00:55:24.580
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Yeah.

00:55:24.580 --> 00:55:26.110
Yes, those sort of tech -- it
depends on who your audience is.

00:55:26.110 --> 00:55:30.940
For a general audience,
the point of this is, okay,

00:55:30.940 --> 00:55:34.250
it's a familiar part
of Manhattan now.

00:55:34.250 --> 00:55:37.170
And just the inclusion of this
little girl who just rushed

00:55:37.170 --> 00:55:38.870
into the picture at the
last minute, I said, "Wow,

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:41.170
[laughter] I got to get that."

00:55:44.520 --> 00:55:47.170
&gt;&gt; Female Speaker: Well, I think
you sort of answered this question

00:55:47.170 --> 00:55:50.920
in a few ways, but I
wanted to ask it again.

00:55:50.920 --> 00:55:53.910
You used the phrase
documentary a number of times.

00:55:53.910 --> 00:55:57.320
And so -- and you reference it, and
this is a good example [inaudible].

00:55:57.320 --> 00:56:01.250
How much -- you say an
architect might have a vision,

00:56:01.250 --> 00:56:04.380
and you sort of have a way
that you like to shoot.

00:56:04.380 --> 00:56:06.900
Is the way that you
like to shoot to --

00:56:06.900 --> 00:56:10.570
is it important to you to
have it being documentary

00:56:10.570 --> 00:56:12.750 position:56%
so that it's as correct as possible?

00:56:12.750 --> 00:56:14.510
So you had fun with the fish eye.

00:56:14.510 --> 00:56:17.490
But as part of your motivation
and the photographs that you take

00:56:17.490 --> 00:56:20.820
that you would like for it
to be perspective corrected

00:56:20.820 --> 00:56:23.430 position:56%
and that you're trying to make it --

00:56:23.430 --> 00:56:26.310
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: I just start
-- I just -- well, the main --

00:56:26.310 --> 00:56:27.610
&gt;&gt; Female Speaker: How
does that [inaudible]?

00:56:27.610 --> 00:56:28.910 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: The main -- yeah.

00:56:28.910 --> 00:56:32.230
The main objective simply would
be to produce a photograph

00:56:32.230 --> 00:56:37.960
that is comfortable enough that
the fewer is not preoccupied

00:56:37.960 --> 00:56:39.880
with the method that has been used

00:56:39.880 --> 00:56:41.930
to document the thing
in the first place.

00:56:41.930 --> 00:56:43.620
You know, you -- in other words,

00:56:43.620 --> 00:56:45.460
when you look at an
architectural photographer --

00:56:45.460 --> 00:56:48.870
a photograph, you want
the viewer to say, "Ooh,

00:56:48.870 --> 00:56:50.530
that's a great looking building.

00:56:50.530 --> 00:56:52.390
That's terrific."

00:56:52.390 --> 00:56:55.230
You don't want them to
say, "Wow, I wonder --

00:56:55.230 --> 00:56:56.530
that's a marvelous photograph.

00:56:56.530 --> 00:57:00.220
I wonder how that was done."

00:57:00.220 --> 00:57:03.980
Then maybe the photographer
has overdone it

00:57:03.980 --> 00:57:07.850
because then the photograph
itself becomes more important

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:09.150
than the subject.

00:57:09.150 --> 00:57:11.980 position:56%
And that's a -- that's one of the --

00:57:11.980 --> 00:57:14.090
one of the big quandaries

00:57:14.090 --> 00:57:17.170
with architectural
photography in general.

00:57:17.170 --> 00:57:21.110
And it's one of the reasons
that architectural photographers

00:57:21.110 --> 00:57:26.710
in general are not as widely
known to the general public

00:57:26.710 --> 00:57:29.970
as photographers in
some other fields.

00:57:32.290 --> 00:57:33.590
Ford?

00:57:33.590 --> 00:57:36.900
&gt;&gt; Ford Peatross: Has that client
dynamic that you just described

00:57:36.900 --> 00:57:41.900
over 50 years had any major shifts,
or is it still pretty steady?

00:57:47.380 --> 00:57:52.410
&gt;&gt; Norman McGrath: Well, it -- I
mean one thing that it has done is

00:57:52.410 --> 00:57:59.450 position:56%
that because in fact many even
modest sized architectural firms can

00:57:59.450 --> 00:58:07.100
afford to go out and buy a $3,000
camera like this and a $2,000 lens,

00:58:07.100 --> 00:58:09.960
you know, $5,000 sounds
like a lot of money.

00:58:09.960 --> 00:58:13.740
But if that permits you to
get good quality photographs,

00:58:13.740 --> 00:58:18.280
then a moderately skilled
photographer

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:25.490
who is not necessarily
professional can go out and capture

00:58:25.490 --> 00:58:31.210
for an architect photographs
which are quite adequate for use

00:58:31.210 --> 00:58:34.940
on a website or for reference
purposes, not necessarily

00:58:34.940 --> 00:58:37.190
for publication, but maybe I
mean if they're good enough,

00:58:37.190 --> 00:58:39.680
they could be for publication too.

00:58:39.680 --> 00:58:44.000
So that -- I think architects
in general are doing more

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:47.870
of their own photography than
has been true in the past.

00:58:47.870 --> 00:58:53.390 position:56%
They are doing it now because this
is an infinitely easier to learn how

00:58:53.390 --> 00:58:57.920
to use and to use than a four
by five view camera ever was.

